Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Boil a half-full #kettle{}.

Peel and grate the @garlic{3%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}). Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{80%g} and roughly chop the @hazelnuts{50%g}, then add both to a large #bowl{} and set aside.

Put the @dried porcini mushrooms{5} and @boiling water for the mushrooms{20%ml} into a small bowl and leave to soak.

Put the @diced sweet potato{300%g} onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and tender, ~{18-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop them onto another large baking tray. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Roast on the middle shelf until golden, ~{30-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

While they roast, halve the @red cabbage{1/2}, cut out and discard the tough core, then finely slice.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the cabbage and cook, stirring frequently, until it starts to soften, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add the @water for the cabbage{200%ml}, then lower the heat and simmer until tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

While the cabbage simmers, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat.

Once hot, add the @closed cup mushrooms{150%g} and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Fry, stirring occasionally, until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and @dried rosemary{1}. Cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Once cooked, transfer to the bowl of cheese and nuts - keep the pan, you'll use it again.

Pop a small saucepan on medium-high heat and add the @butter{30%g}. Melt gently, then stir in the @plain flour{2%tbsp}. Continue to stir until combined, you've made a roux!

Cook, stirring, until the roux is a medium brown colour, ~{3-4%minutes}. Gradually stir in the @water for the gravy{400%ml}, then stir in the @vegetable stock paste{20%g} and bring to the boil, stirring out any lumps that form.

Lower the heat and simmer, stirring occasionally, until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Once the sweet potato is cooked, add it to the bowl with the cheese, nuts and mushrooms. Using the back of a #fork{}, roughly mash some of the sweet potato, leaving other chunks whole.

Add the @panko breadcrumbs{25%g} and soaked porcini mushrooms (including their liquid) to the bowl. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}, then mix well.

Transfer the nut roast mixture to an appropriately sized and lightly oiled #baking dish{}. Use the back of a #spoon{} to press the mixture into the dish. Drizzle with a little @oil{} and bake on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Once the cabbage is cooked, stir through the @redcurrant jelly{50%g}, season with @salt{} and remove from the heat.

Trim the @green beans{150%g}. When the nut roast has 8 mins remaining, pop the #mushroom pan{} back on medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

Once hot, add the green beans and fry until starting to char, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add a splash of @water{} and immediately cover with a #lid{} or some #foil{}. Cook until tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}.

When everything's ready, reheat the cabbage and gravy if needed, then share your ultimate nut roast between your plates with the roast potatoes, redcurrant cabbage and green beans alongside. Pour over the gravy to finish.

Enjoy!